  "answer": "**Iqbal stages sorrow as life's essential polish and awakener:** In *Falsafa-e-Gham* (\"The Philosophy of Sorrow\"), he argues that grief is not mere affliction but a transformative force—the \"spirit's light,\" a \"plectrum\" that tunes the soul's instrument, wings for the heart's flight, and ultimately \"a silent song of soul\" that completes human music.[^1]\n\n**Ghalib retorts, refusing consolation or transcendence:** From his ghazal \"Dard minnat-kash-e-dawa na hua,\" he counters: \"My pain would not be indebted to a cure; / I did not heal, nor did my state grow worse.\"[^2] Where Iqbal philosophizes sorrow into grace and wholeness, Ghalib clings to its raw persistence, scorning any remedy that might dilute or resolve it—grief endures as grief, unphilosophized, a stubborn debtor to itself.\n\nIqbal insists sorrow elevates: it scatters life's illusions, reveals secrets, and perfects the human form. Ghalib dwells in the unyielding ache, his heart a site of pain's sovereignty, where even stasis (\"nor did my state grow worse\") is victory over cure's intrusion. The philosopher builds a metaphysics of mourning; the poet luxuriates in its unbuilt ruins.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch.7 \"Falsafa-e-Gham\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/07-falsafa-e-gham/translation/#p-141d8d)).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch.26 \"Dard minnat-kash-e-dawa na hua\" ([paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/26-dard-minnat-kash-e-dawa-na-hua/translation/#p-fd05a7)).",
